<!DOCTYPE html><html lang="en"><head><meta charset="utf-8" /><title>Multidimensional Arrays</title><style type="text/css">body {	font-family: courier, monospace;	color:#FF6633;	}	.instructions {	color: #666666;	font-family: georgia, serif;	}	code {	color: #444;	font-weight: bold;	font-size: 1.1em;}</style></head><body><header><h1 class="instructions">Multidimensional Arrays</h1></header><article><h2 class="instructions">Building Multidimensional Arrays</h2><p class="instructions">Multidimensional arrays are essentially "nested" arrays. The parent array has array elements that are arrays in themselves!</p><h3 class="instructions">Array 1</h3><p class="instructions">Write a multidimensional array for $random_image that puts in caption and alt text information. The alt text is to customize the required alt attribute in the img tag, and the caption is to put customized captions beneath every image. Notice that the nested arrays are indexed arrays, and their array elements are associative. If you put the image in the code>figure</code> tag, you can use <code>figcaption</code> for the caption. If the image isn't a figure, just put it in a paragraph.</p><!-- write script for multidimensional array 1 here and use print_r() to view it. --><?php$random_image = array(	array('filename' => 'blue.gif', 'alt' => 'blue rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Blue Rectangle!'),	array('filename' => 'green.gif', 'alt' => 'green rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Green Rectangle!'),	array('filename' => 'orange.gif', 'alt' => 'orange rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Orange Rectangle!'),	array('filename' => 'pink.gif', 'alt' => 'pink rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Pink Rectangle!'),	array('filename' => 'red.gif', 'alt' => 'red rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Red Rectangle!'),	array('filename' => 'yellow.gif', 'alt' => 'yellow rectangle', 'caption' => 'Big Yellow Rectangle!')	);echo '<pre>';print_r($random_image);echo '</pre>';$random_key = array_rand($random_image);?><p class="instructions">Now, write a script that outputs "blue rectangle." Remember that you have to specify two keys: one for the first array, and one for the second. (You're asking for the array that holds the blue image information, and then for the array element that holds the value 'blue rectangle').</p><!-- write script here --><?php echo $random_image[0]['alt'];?><h3 class="instructions">Array 2</h3><p class="instructions">Write a multidimensional array for $meals that has 4 nested arrays. Each of the nested arrays is an associative array with 3 array elements: breakfast, lunch and dinner. Nested array one has the values: oatmeal, poached eggs, toast and waffles. Nested array two has the values: ham sandwich, burrito, cheeseburger and spinach salad. Nested array three has the values: spaghetti, roast beef, pizza and mac 'n' cheese. Use <code>print_r()</code> function to view your multidimensional array. Don't forget to use the preformatted text tag to help make the output more readable.</p><!-- write script for multidimensional array 2 here, and use print_r() to view it.  --><?php $meals = array(	'breakfast' => array('oatmeal', 'poached egg', 'toast', 'waffles'),	'lunch' => array('ham sandwich', 'burrito', 'cheeseburger', 'spinach salad'),	'dinner' => array('spaghetti', 'roast beef', 'pizza', 'mac \'n\' cheese')	);echo '<pre>';print_r($meals);echo '</pre>';?><p class="instructions">Now, write a script that outputs "pizza." Remember that you have to specify two keys: one for the first array, and one for the second. (You're asking for the array that holds dinner values, and then for the nested array element that holds the value 'pizza').</p><!-- write script here --><?phpecho $meals['dinner'][2];?><h2 class="instructions">Using Multidimensional Arrays</h2><p class="instructions">Write a script to output a random image using your <code>$random_image</code> multidimensional array. Output the image using a paragraph for the caption since this isn't really a figure. You'll need to use the <code>array_rand()</code> function.</p><p class="instructions">Note that you are randomizing only the "parent" arrays, not the elements in the nested arrays. You'll get a random image with the information relevant to it; you know what the keys are that you want for the alt text and caption, so you ask for them. The random key is for retrieving the random image itself. You'll be outputting the values for variables in the image tag markup and paragraph markup itself, so write that markup in the page.</p><img src="/php424/10multidimensional-arrays/images/<?php echo $random_image[$random_key]['filename']; ?>" alt="<?php echo $random_image[$random_key]['alt']; ?>" /><p><?php echo $random_image[$random_key]['caption']; ?></p><p class="instructions">Write a script to output a random menu using your <code>$meals</code> multidimensional array. Output the random meal in the text below.</p><p class="instructions">Note that you are randomizing the elements in the nested array, not parent arrays. You'll ask specifically for the particular meal you want to randomize, and put the random key in for the actual food item.</p><!-- write script  here --><?php$random_breakfast = array_rand($meals['breakfast']);$random_lunch = array_rand($meals['lunch']);$random_dinner = array_rand($meals['dinner']);?><!-- put the output in this text --><p><strong>Menu Bot</strong> has formulated the perfect daily meal for you! For breakfast you'll have <?php echo $meals['breakfast'][$random_breakfast];?>, for lunch you'll have <?php echo $meals['lunch'][$random_lunch];?> and for dinner you'll have <?php echo $meals['dinner'][$random_dinner];?>.</p></article></body></html>